14 (2025 Replacement Volume)
15 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
16 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
17 Article – Commercial Law
18 13–301.
19 Unfair, abusive, or deceptive trade practices include any:
20 (14) Violation of a provision of:
21 (xlvii) Title 14, Subtitle 50 of this article; [or]
22 (xlviii) Section 13–411.1(c)(2) of the Transportation Article; or
23 (XLIX) SECTION 14–1330 OF THIS ARTICLE; OR
24 14–1330.
25 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION, THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
26 INDICATED.
27 (2) “CONSUMER GOODS” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 13–101 OF
28 THIS ARTICLE.
29 (3) “ESSENTIAL CONSUMER GOOD” MEANS:
30 (I) FOOD, INCLUDING HUMAN AND ANIMAL FOOD;

HOUSE BILL 191 3
1 (II) WATER, INCLUDING ICE, AND OTHER BEVERAGES;
2 (III) PERSONAL HYGIENE PRODUCTS, INCLUDING TOILETRIES
3 AND CLEANING PRODUCTS;
4 (IV) HEALTH PRODUCTS, INCLUDING MEDICINE, MEDICAL
5 SUPPLIES AND EQUIPMENT, AND PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT; AND
6 (V) FUEL.
7 (4) “MERCHANT MERCHANT” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 13–101
8 OF THIS ARTICLE.
9 (5) “RETAIL ESTABLISHMENT” MEANS AN ESTABLISHMENT THAT
10 SELLS CONSUMER GOODS TO THE PUBLIC.
11 (B) (1) THIS SECTION APPLIES ONLY TO AN IN–PERSON RETAIL
12 TRANSACTION AT A RETAIL ESTABLISHMENT TOTALING AT LEAST $5 AND LESS THAN
13 $300.
14 (2) THIS SECTION DOES NOT APPLY TO:
15 (I) A TELEPHONE, MAIL, OR INTERNET TRANSACTION; OR
16 (II) A VENDING MACHINE OR KIOSK TRANSACTION; OR
17 (III) A TRANSACTION WITH A MERCHANT THAT SELLS TO THE
18 PUBLIC PRIMARILY:
19 1. FOOD OR BEVERAGES FOR ON–PREMISES
20 CONSUMPTION; OR
21 2. A LIMITED VARIETY OF GOURMET OR SPECIALTY
22 FOODS, INCLUDING CHEESES, FRUITS, NUTS, CANDY, SPICES, AND OILS; OR
23 (IV) THE PURCHASE OF FUEL FROM A MERCHANT THAT SELLS
24 FUEL TO THE PUBLIC BUT REQUIRES A PAID MEMBERSHIP TO PURCHASE THE FUEL.
25 (II) A TRANSACTION TO PAY TO PARK A VEHICLE IN:
26 1. A PARKING LOT OR GARAGE; OR
27 2. A METERED PARKING SPACE.

4 HOUSE BILL 191
1 (C) A EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN SUBSECTION (D) OF THIS SECTION, BETWEEN
2 THE HOURS OF 6 A.M. AND 10 P.M. A MERCHANT MAY NOT:
3 (1) PROHIBIT A PERSON FROM MAKING A CASH PAYMENT TO
4 PURCHASE A AN ESSENTIAL CONSUMER GOOD OR SERVICE;
5 (2) REQUIRE A PERSON TO USE A CREDIT OR DEBIT CARD TO
6 PURCHASE A AN ESSENTIAL CONSUMER GOOD OR SERVICE; OR
7 (3) CHARGE OR COLLECT FROM A PERSON A HIGHER PRICE THAN
8 CHARGED OR COLLECTED FOR AN EQUIVALENT CASHLESS TRANSACTION, WHETHER
9 OR NOT THE DIFFERENCE IN PRICE IS DESCRIBED AS A FEE, FOR MAKING A CASH
10 PAYMENT FOR THE PURCHASE OF A AN ESSENTIAL CONSUMER GOOD OR SERVICE.
11 (D) (1) A MERCHANT MAY PROHIBIT A PERSON FROM MAKING A CASH
12 PAYMENT FOR THE PURCHASE OF A CONSUMER GOOD:
13 (1) (I) IN A CASH DENOMINATION GREATER THAN $20; OR
14 (2) (II) IF THE MERCHANT:
15 (I) 1. PROVIDES AND MAINTAINS A DEVICE ON THE
16 PREMISES OF THE ESTABLISHMENT THAT CONVERTS CASH INTO A PREPAID CARD
17 THAT A PERSON MAY USE TO PURCHASE A CONSUMER GOOD AT THE
18 ESTABLISHMENT;
19 (II) 2. DOES NOT CHARGE ANY FEE OR REQUIRE A DEPOSIT;
20 AND
21 (III) 3. IF THE DEVICE MALFUNCTIONS OR BECOMES
22 INOPERABLE, ACCEPTS PAYMENT IN CASH IN ACCORDANCE WITH THIS SECTION
23 UNTIL THE DEVICE RESUMES NORMAL OPERATIONS.
24 (2) A MERCHANT MAY COLLECT FROM A PERSON AN ADDITIONAL
25 AMOUNT NOT EXCEEDING 4 CENTS WHEN ROUNDING THE PRICE FOR AN ESSENTIAL
26 CONSUMER GOOD IN ACCORDANCE WITH APPLICABLE LAW.
27 (D) (E) A VIOLATION OF THIS SECTION IS:
28 (1) AN UNFAIR, ABUSIVE, OR DECEPTIVE TRADE PRACTICE WITHIN
29 THE MEANING OF TITLE 13 OF THIS ARTICLE; AND

HOUSE BILL 191 5
1 (2) EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN SUBSECTION (E) (F) OF THIS SECTION,
2 SUBJECT TO THE ENFORCEMENT AND PENALTY PROVISIONS CONTAINED IN TITLE
3 13 OF THIS ARTICLE.
4 (E) (F) (1) SECTIONS 13–410(A) AND (B) AND 13–411 OF THIS ARTICLE
5 DO NOT APPLY TO A VIOLATION OF THIS SECTION.
6 (2) THE DIVISION OF CONSUMER PROTECTION OF THE OFFICE OF
7 THE ATTORNEY GENERAL SHALL PROVIDE A MERCHANT WHO VIOLATES THIS
8 SECTION WITH AT LEAST TWO SEPARATE OPPORTUNITIES TO COMPLY WITH THE
9 REQUIREMENTS OF THIS SECTION.
10 (3) (I) A MERCHANT WHO VIOLATES THIS SECTION AFTER TWO
11 SEPARATE OPPORTUNITIES TO COMPLY UNDER PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS
12 SUBSECTION IS SUBJECT TO A FINE NOT EXCEEDING $5,000 $500 FOR EACH
13 VIOLATION.
14 (II) A MERCHANT WHO VIOLATES THIS SECTION AFTER HAVING
15 BEEN FINED UNDER SUBPARAGRAPH (I) OF THIS PARAGRAPH IS SUBJECT TO A FINE
16 NOT EXCEEDING $10,000 $1,000 FOR EACH SUBSEQUENT VIOLATION.
17 (III) THE FINES PROVIDED FOR IN SUBPARAGRAPHS (I) AND (II)
18 OF THIS PARAGRAPH:
19 1. ARE CIVIL PENALTIES RECOVERABLE IN
20 ACCORDANCE WITH § 13–410(C) OF THIS ARTICLE; AND
21 2. SHALL BE SET IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 13–410(D) OF
22 THIS ARTICLE.
23 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
24 October 1, 2026.
Approved:
